2)Murderous Angels (O’Brien)
{{https://pictures.abebooks.com/SEVENHENS/md/md1011098257.jpg}}

To create an icon is to freeze identity. How do we arrive at a supple understanding of such an iconic figure as Patrice Lumumba? Raoul Peck has chosen to portray the Congolese hero in two genres, an experimental documentary and a fictional feature film. Through a close reading of the two films, with an emphasis on the evolution from one genre to the other, I contend that neither film should be considered in isolation and that Peck's “truth” about Lumumba lies in the dialectical relationship between the two films. In addition to Peck's use of genre to challenge a univocal vision of the man and the politician, a comparison of the gender dynamics in Peck's two Lumumba films sheds light not only on the figure of Lumumba but also on the constraints and freedoms of generic choices. In his documentary (Lumumba: La Mort du prophète, 1992) Peck foregrounds his personal connections to post-independence Congo and accords a place of honor to his mother's voice with the regular refrain “Ma mère raconte.” In his Hollywoodian biopic/political thriller (Lumumba, 2000) Peck places greater emphasis on Lumumba's masculinity, on the rehabilitation of his masculine dignity in the face of the humiliations and degradations suffered under colonialism, forms of suffering that have often been coded as emasculating rather than simply dehumanizing. This I will argue building on the two chapters of my book Gender and Decolonization in the Congo: The Legacy of Patrice Lumumba (Palgrave Macmillian, 2010) dedicated to Peck's work. The broader frame of the book, that will help shape my analysis of the two films, emphasizes the need to broaden our understanding of Patrice Lumumba by including the roles played by women in the period preceding and following the Congo's accession to independence in addition to examining representations of Lumumba's masculinity, as defined in his relationships to both women and men.

(Karen Bouwer, born and raised in South Africa, is Professor of French in the Department of Modern and Classical Languages at the University of San Francisco. She received her Ph.D. from Michigan State University in 1994)

