Wilhelm Arnold von Mallinckrodt (Cologne, 1864-Frankfurt am Main, 1930), descendant of a German entrepreneurial family, settled in Antwerp in the 1880s. He married in 1888 to Eugénie Charlotte “Hortense” Günther (Antwerp, 1867-Vachendorf am Chiemsee, 1943), who gave birth to four children, born between 1889 and 1901. He was an agent of the Dresdner Bank in the 1890s, circa 1900 bank W. Mallinckrodt and C °, and was also manager of the Banque Centrale Anversoise. With the Société Générale de Commerce, Mallinckrodt traded in coffee, wool and rubber. The banker-businessman was one of the most prominent and wealthy members of the German colony in Antwerp, active in associations, philanthropy and patronage. In 1918, the Belgian State placed his possessions under a sekwester, which was dissolved in 1920.

