Alexandre Galopin (1879-1944), was governor of Société Générale de Belgique (since 1935), a private bank that managed many compagnies in Congo, and Galopin was also governor of Union Minière (since 1939), a mining compagnie in Congo with a contested colonial past. The compagnie was also responsible of the mining of uranium, an important ingredient for the atomic bomb. They transported uranium to the US, but also, behind the screen, they transported at least 1695 ton of uranium to Nazi-Germany. The most of the uranium for Germany, were found back by US-forces and transported to Oak Ridge, for nuclear enrichment for US construction of the atomic bomb. Galopin and his co-workers, were never condemned for their economic collaboration with Nazi-Germany, and neither for their colonial past. He was murdered in 1944 by a group of right-wing extremists at the command of Robert Verbelen.
{{https://www.belgiumwwii.be/image/content/31595.jpg}}
(Van Rossem, J.P. (2011). Belgisch uranium voor de eerste Amerikaanse en Russische atoombommen. Kessel-Lo: Uitgeverij Van Halewyck, p. 127)

