The Maria Hendrikapark is a park in the Belgian city of Ostend. The park was created at the request of King Leopold II, who initially wanted to call the park Bois de Boulogne after the famous landscape park on the edge of Paris. The park was eventually named after Leopold's wife Maria Hendrika of Austria.

The park was built on the site of a wild piece of forest, just outside the old city walls, south of the barracks. The design was by the German landscape architect Édouard Keilig. At the king's insistence, in 1886 the Belgian government handed over the plot of land on which the park was realized. The park was then 27 hectares. The first works were finished in 1892. The "Avenue de la Reine" now connected the park with the seawall and the Royal Chalet, one of the wishes of Leopold II. At the end of July 1892, both "Koninginnelaan" and Maria Hendrikapark were officially opened. The buildings had transformed the park into a recreational area where you could walk or ride on the paths. To increase the attractiveness, a café-restaurant was built on the island of the pond, the "Laiterie Royale" (the current "Koninginnehof", or popularly still "t Laiterietje"). Sport and culture were also considered when constructing the park. A second drinking place, linked to a militia association, was the Armenonville (still in existence). In a shed, previously used by the sculptors of the Count de Smet de Naeyerbruggen, a historical museum, the Liebaert Museum (disappeared), was built. Along the canal on the east side came the clubhouse of the local rowing club (disappeared). There was also a swimming school, the Free Swimmers Ostend, but this has disappeared with the recent renovation.

